Ah, that's good feedback! In that case, I'd definitely recommend starting with "Operating Systems: Three Easy Pieces" (OSTEP). It's more advanced than "Code" but maintains an engaging style. The authors deliberately wrote it to be accessible while covering serious OS concepts.

The book is broken into three main pieces:
- Virtualization (CPU, Memory)
- Concurrency
- Persistence (File Systems, I/O)

It would help you understand concepts like why we care about block sizes (like in your code), how memory management works, and why certain performance optimizations matter.

You can actually check it out for free online first (ostep.org) to see if you like the writing style, and then get the Kindle version if you prefer that format.

If you find OSTEP engaging, then "The Design and Implementation of the FreeBSD Operating System" would be a great next step - it's more advanced and shows how these concepts are implemented in a real-world OS.

Both these books are more sophisticated than "Code" but maintain readability and real-world relevance.
